    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-10-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-10-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="395"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d395">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 (E. W.)/11–742: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Admiral <persName type="from">William D. Leahy</persName>,
                        Chief of Staff to the Commander in Chief of the Army and Navy, to the Consul
                        General at Algiers (<persName type="to">Cole</persName>)</hi>
                    <note n="88" xml:id="d395fn88">Copy supplied by the Office of the Secretary of
                        Defense under cover of letter of September 7, 1960.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-10-17">October 17,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>No. M–2. From Handy for Murphy. Copies for Murphy and Eisenhower. This is reply
                    to Murphy’s message of 15 October. <pb facs="0403" n="397" xml:id="pg_397"/>
                    Inform your contact we also have information that Germany contemplates
                    occupation of African Colonies and it is our opinion that Darlan should resist
                    aggression by Axis with Army and Navy in which event America will provide at
                    once large scale military, material, and economic aid in the colonies.</p>
                <p>Inform Giraud’s contact that question of command of French Army and Navy should
                    be settled by Frenchmen and that America will undertake a large scale operation
                    immediately upon resistance by French to Axis invasion of the Colonies.</p>
                <p>Proposal that officers of American Staff visit Algeria has already been approved
                    by Eisenhower, details will be cabled by Marshall.</p>
                <p>In regard to the General’s departure via submarine it is considered that airplane
                    passage is preferable, less subject to interruption, and more easily arranged.
                    [Handy.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Leahy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
